tion centers on human beings and their place in the larger cosmic whole as well as on how a proper organization of human life in political association provides the conditions whereby human beings might achieve their purpose.Summary of Plato's "Laws" gives an account of the first nine books of Plato's Laws. Alfarabi explains Plato's art of writing in general and the method he follows in writing the Laws in particular. Unlike Alfarabi's other works, which examine the place of legislation and laws in the broader context of political philosophy, the Summary is a more specialized study of the question of laws and how and why they are formulated, with a particular focus on the relevance of Plato's investigation concerning Greek divine laws for the study and understanding of all divine laws.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 08. Jul 2019) 0aIslamic philosophyvEarly works to 1800. 0aPolitical sciencexPhilosophyvEarly works to 1800. 4aPhilosophy. 4aPolitical Science & Political History. 7aPHILOSOPHY / Individual Philosophers.2bisacsh1 aButterworth, Charles E.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCOR eBook-Package 2000-2015z978311066750908iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCornell Univ. Press eBook-Package Pilot Project 2014-2015z978311060674440uhttps://doi.org/10.7591/9781501700323423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9781501700323.jpg  a978-3-11-060674-4  Cornell Univ. Press eBook-Package Pilot Project 2014-2015c2014d2015  a978-3-11-066750-9  COR eBook-Package 2000-2015  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_PLTLJSIS  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_PLTLJSIS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA14ALL  aPDA16SSH  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA1ALL  aPDA2  aPDA2HUM  aPDA5EBK  aPDA7ENG